    mc("In quantitative research, a larger sample size generally:","Makes research harder","Increases statistical power and reduces margin of error, making results more reliable and generalizable","Has no effect on results","Reduces validity",1,"Larger sample: more statistical power (ability to detect true effects), smaller confidence intervals, more representative of population. Key consideration in quantitative research design."),
    mc("The AP Research oral defense requires students to:","Recite the paper from memory","Present research and defend the methodology, findings, and conclusions in a Q&A with evaluators","Write an additional essay","Present to other students only",1,"Oral defense: 15-20 minute presentation + Q&A with teacher-evaluator. Students must explain their choices, defend their methodology, respond to challenges, and demonstrate deep ownership of their research."),
    mc("A 'case study' research design is most appropriate when:","You need to generalize to a large population","You want to examine a specific phenomenon in depth within its real-world context","You need a control group","You want to establish causation",1,"Case study: in-depth investigation of a specific case (person, organization, event, program) in its context. Best for 'how' and 'why' questions. Limited generalizability but rich in detail."),
    mc("Which section of an AP Research paper states explicitly why the study matters?","Methodology","Literature review","Significance statement (usually in the Introduction)","Findings",2,"Significance: in the Introduction, you explain why this gap matters — what will be gained by answering this question? What contribution does it make to the field?"),
    mc("A primary source in research is:","A textbook summarizing research","Original, firsthand data or accounts (raw data, interviews, diaries, original experiments, artifacts)","A peer-reviewed review article","A news report about a study",1,"Primary sources: original data, first-hand accounts. Secondary: analyze/interpret primary sources. Tertiary: compile secondary sources. AP Research values primary data when possible."),
